class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP Film and Television Music Award for Top Television Series]]\n| ''[[Eureka (U.S. TV series)|Eureka]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for Television]]\n| ''[[Caprica (TV series)|Caprica]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for Television]]\n| ''[[Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series)|Battlestar Galactica]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for Television]]\n| ''[[Human Target (2010 TV series)|Human Target]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Video Game or Interactive Media]]\n| ''[[Dark Void]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]]\n| ''Human Target''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Video Game or Interactive Media]]\n| ''[[SOCOM 4: U.S. Navy SEALs]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP Film and Television Music Award for Top Television Series]]\n| ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for Television]]\n| ''[[Da Vinci's Demons]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]]\n| ''Da Vinci's Demons''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]]\n| ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Composition for a Series]]\n| ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0566970}}\n*[http://www.bearmccreary.com Official website]\n*[http://www.vgmonline.net/bearmccrearyinterview-2/ MAFgest 2016 interview]\n*[http://www.geekson.com/archives/archiveepisodes/2005/episode100305.htm Audio Interview] on GeeksOn!\n*[https://www.academia.edu/7231992/Of_Duduks_and_Dylan_Negotiating_Music_and_the_Aural_Space_in_Battlestar_Galactica \"Of Duduks and Dylan: Negotiating Music and the Aural Space in ''Battlestar Galactica''''], by Eftychia Papanikolaou; chapter in ''Cylons in America: Critical Studies of Battlestar Galactica'', edited by Tiffany Potter and C. W. Marshall, 224\u2013236. New York and London: Continuum, 2007.\n\n{{Bear McCreary}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCreary, Bear}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American accordionists]]\n[[Category:American film score composers]]\n[[Category:American people of Armenian descent]]\n[[Category:American television composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male television composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Bellingham, Washington]]\n[[Category:Thornton School of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century accordionists]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American composer and musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image        = McCrearyHeadshot2009.jpg\n| alt          = Portrait photograph of Bear McCreary\n| caption      = McCreary in 2009\n| name         = Bear McCreary\n| background   = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1979|2|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], United States\n| years_active = 1998\u2013present\n| label        = La La Land Records, Sparks and Shadows\n| occupation   = Composer, conductor\n| genre        = [[Film score]], [[orchestral]]\n}}\n\n'''Bear McCreary''' (born February 17, 1979) is an American musician and composer of film, television, and video games scores based in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. He is best known for his work on the [[Remake#Television|reimagined]] ''[[Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series)|Battlestar Galactica]]'' television series and for the TV series ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]'' and ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''. He has also scored for the [[PlayStation 4]] video game ''[[God of War (2018 video game)|God of War]]''.\nMcCreary won an Emmy for his main title of ''[[Da Vinci's Demons]]''.<ref name=\"emmys-2013\">{{cite news |last= Weisman |first= Jon| title= LIVE From the Creative Arts Emmys|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/emmys-creative-arts-emmys-live-blog-1200612516/ |work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> His most recent Emmy nomination was in 2015 for Outstanding Music Composition for a Series for season one of ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]''.<ref name=\"Emmy Award Nominees and Winners-2015\">{{cite web|title=67th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2015/outstanding-music-composition-for-a-series-original-dramatic-score| publisher= [[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|Television Academy]]| accessdate= October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMcCreary was born in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], and spent most of his formative years in [[Bellingham, Washington]]. He is the son of author [[Laura Kalpakian]] and professor Jay McCreary of University of Hawaii. His brother, Brendan McCreary, is also a musician. Bear has directed and produced several music videos for Brendan's band, Young Beautiful in a Hurry.<ref>{{cite web|title= 'I Don't Want to Die a Virgin' Music Video!| date= October 13, 2011 |url= http://www.bearmccreary.com/#blog/films/i-dont-want-to-die-a-virgin-music-video/ |publisher= BearMcCreary.com| first= Bear| last= McCreary| accessdate= December 6, 2017}}</ref> He graduated from [[Bellingham High School (Washington)|Bellingham High School]] in 1997.<ref name=Stars>{{cite web| url= http://www.bearmccreary.com/#articles/bellingham-herald-january-12-2005/| via= BearMcCreary.com| work= The Bellingham Herald| title= Score for the Stars: Bellingham High grad now composes for 'Battlestar Galatica{{sic|hide=y}}'| first= Kie| last= Relyea| date= January 12, 2005| access-date= December 6, 2017| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171029053811/http://www.bearmccreary.com/#articles/bellingham-herald-january-12-2005/| archivedate= October 29, 2017| url-status= dead| df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is a classically trained pianist and self-taught [[accordionist]].<ref name= Stars /><ref name= Scorekeeper>{{cite web| url= http://www.aintitcool.com/node/23532| title= ScoreKeeper interviews ''Battlestar Galactica''{{'}}s Bear McCreary!!!| date= June 7, 2006| first= Bear| last= McCreary | publisher= [[AintItCool.com]]| interviewer= ScoreKeeper| access-date= December 6, 2017}}</ref> He studied under the renowned [[film score]] composer [[Elmer Bernstein]] during which time he reconstructed and reorchestrated Bernstein's 1963 score for ''[[Kings of the Sun]]''.  Their collaboration allowed for the complete score to be available as a soundtrack album for the first time in 40 years.<ref name=\"Biog\">{{cite web|title=Biography| url= http://www.bearmccreary.com | publisher= BearMcCreary.com|accessdate=April 13, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090406081712/http://www.bearmccreary.com/|archivedate=April 6, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Television===\n\n====''Battlestar Galactica'' and ''Caprica''====\n{{main|Music of Battlestar Galactica (reimagining)|Music of Caprica}}\n\nIn 2003, McCreary worked under primary composer [[Richard Gibbs]] on the [[Battlestar Galactica (TV miniseries)|three-hour miniseries]] which served as a pilot for the reimagined series of ''[[Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series)|Battlestar Galactica]]''. When the show was picked up, Gibbs opted not to devote full-time to the regular series' production, and McCreary became the sole composer. He worked on the series until it reached its conclusion in 2009, scoring over 70 episodes. To date, six ''Battlestar Galactica'' soundtrack albums have been released, and have garnered a great deal of critical acclaim<ref name=\"sep080622\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Sepinwall on TV: Michael Giacchino and Bear McCreary, score keepers|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2008/06/sepinwall_on_tv_michael_giacch.html |work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |accessdate=March 18, 2009|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090321130959/http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2008/06/sepinwall_on_tv_michael_giacch.html|archivedate=March 21, 2009|date=June 22, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ct080616\">{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|title='Battlestar Galactica' provides some Earth-shattering 'Revelations'|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2008/06/battlestar-ga-1.html|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]| accessdate= March 18, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329055809/http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2008/06/battlestar-ga-1.html|archivedate=March 29, 2009|date=June 16, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and commercial success. The soundtracks for [[Battlestar Galactica (season 2)|seasons two]] and [[Battlestar Galactica (season 3)|three]] ranked amongst [[Amazon.com]]'s Top 30 Music Sales on their first days of release.<ref name=\"Biog\"/>\n\nMcCreary composed for the ''Battlestar Galactica'' prequel series ''[[Caprica (TV series)|Caprica]]'' and ''[[Battlestar Galactica: Blood and Chrome]]''.\n\n====''Human Target''====\nMcCreary provided the score for the series ''[[Human Target (2010 TV series)|Human Target]]'' (based on [[Human Target|the comic book of the same name]]). The pilot episode and main theme score had been recorded with a full orchestra.<ref>{{cite web| last= McCreary| first= Bear| title=Human Target Screens Today|url=http://www.bearmccreary.com/blog/?p=2532#comment-4702| publisher= BearMcCreary.com| accessdate=July 26, 2009|date=July 25, 2009}}</ref> The series has the distinction of having one of the largest orchestras on television.\n\nThe score to the finale of season one, \"Christopher Chance\", used the largest orchestra ever assembled for episodic television, and he took the opportunity to rerecord the main title theme with a new orchestration with this larger ensemble.\n\nIn July 2010, he received his first Emmy nomination for the ''Human Target'' main title.<ref name = emmynomination>{{cite web| last= Burlingame| first=Jon|title=Emmy Music Nominations Announced|url=http://www.filmmusicsociety.org/news_events/features/2010/070810.html| work= FilmMusicSociety.org |accessdate=July 8, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817163328/http://www.filmmusicsociety.org/news_events/features/2010/070810.html|archivedate=August 17, 2010|date=July 8, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a post on his blog on July 25, 2010, McCreary announced the new creative leadership brought in for season two had not asked him to return for it, and he would be leaving the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCreary|first=Bear|title=I Am Leaving 'Human Target' |url= http://www.bearmccreary.com/blog/?p=4354| publisher= BearMcCreary.com|accessdate=|date=July 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Black Sails ====\nThe opening title sequence was composed by McCreary with a backing [[sea shanty]] inspired theme. It accurately features an instrument of the period in the form of the [[hurdy-gurdy]].{{Citation needed|reason=Hurdy Gurdies existed in the 18thc but whether or not they were popular in the locations of this show is unsure to this writer, they were probably out of fashion. If pirates played them is questionable and they certainly are not generally the instrument culturally associated with pirates.|date=January 2020}}\n\n==== Outlander ====\nMcCreary has composed the soundtrack for each of the 5 seasons (2015-) of Outlander with the main title being sung by long time collaborator and partner, Raya Yarbrough. McCreary was nominated for an Emmy for the song \"Sassenach\" in 2015. McCreary and Yarbrough have gained may admirers for their work on this show.\n\n==== Other series ====\nDuring [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]] 2010, Bear McCreary attended panels for [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]'s ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'' and [[NBC]]'s ''[[The Cape (2011 TV series)|The Cape]]'' to announce he would be composing the score for both television series.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.ugo.com/tv/comic-con-2010-the-cape| website= [[Ugo.com]]| title= Comic Con 2010: The Cape Casts a Mighty Shadow |publisher= UGO Entertainment |first= Kevin |last= Fitzpatrick | date= July 23, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100727100218/http://www.ugo.com/tv/comic-con-2010-the-cape | archivedate= July 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/walking-dead-reveals-trailer-taps-bear-mccreary-as-composer.html | url-status= dead| title= 'Walking Dead' reveals trailer, taps Bear McCreary as composer| first= Hanh| last= Nguyen| publisher= [[Zap2it.com]]|  date= July 23, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100828065126/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/walking-dead-reveals-trailer-taps-bear-mccreary-as-composer.html| archivedate= August 28, 2010| access-date= December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2013, McCreary announced that he will compose the score for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s series ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|title='Agents of SHIELD': Clark Gregg's 'commanding presence' calls the tune for composer Bear McCreary|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/07/15/agents-of-shield-bear-mccreary-music/|publisher=Entertainment Weekly| accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref> On September 4, 2015, McCreary released the official ''Agents of SHIELD'' soundtrack publicly.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B014HG067O?redirect=true&ref_=cm_cr_ryp_prd_ttl_sol_0| title= Marvel's Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (Original Soundtrack Album)| date= September 4, 2015| publisher= [[Amazon.com]]| access-date= December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcCreary served as orchestral producer for the rock opera ''[[Metalocalypse: The Doomstar Requiem]]'' airing on [[Adult Swim]] on October 27, 2013. This is a continuation of the Metalocalypse universe following the band [[Dethklok]]. The music features a 50-piece orchestra. The soundtrack was released on October 29, 2013.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://loudwire.com/dethklok-blazing-star-exclusive-song-premiere/| website= Loudwire.com| title= Dethklok, 'Blazing Star' \u2013 Exclusive Song Premiere| first= Graham| last= Hartmann| date= October 17, 2013| publisher= Townsquare Media| access-date= December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Films ===\nMcCreary made his theatrical feature film scoring debut with ''[[Step Up 3D]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Yamato|first=Jen|title=Exclusive: 'Step Up 3D' Billboard Art Premiere!|url=http://www.cinematical.com/2010/07/02/exclusive-step-up-3d-billboard-art-premiere/| publisher= Cinematical.com |accessdate=July 9, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704181403/http://www.cinematical.com/2010/07/02/exclusive-step-up-3d-billboard-art-premiere/|archivedate=July 4, 2010| date= July 2, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has scored several [[direct-to-video]] features, including ''[[Rest Stop (film)|Rest Stop]]'', ''[[Rest Stop: Don't Look Back]]'', and ''[[Wrong Turn 2: Dead End]]''.\n\nBear has scored three films with director [[Joe Lynch (director)|Joe Lynch]] (of ''Wrong Turn 2''), the latest being ''[[Everly (film)|Everly]]'' which includes \"Silent Night\", a [[duet]] with his spouse, Raya Yarbrough.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barton |first=Steve |title=\"Silent Night\" music video by Raya Yarbrough & Bear McCreary, directed by Joe Lynch. |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/92696/everly-shooting-up-home-video-in-april/ |publisher=Dread Central |accessdate=March 10, 2015 |date=March 10, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112424/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/92696/everly-shooting-up-home-video-in-april/ |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> McCreary's latest feature film scores are for ''[[The Cloverfield Paradox]]'', released February 4, 2018, ''[[Tau (film)|Tau]]'' in 2018, and then 2019's ''[[Godzilla: King of the Monsters (2019 film)|Godzilla: King of the Monsters]]'' and ''[[Child's Play (2019 film)|Child's Play]]''.\n\n=== Video games ===\nMcCreary made an eight-bit rendition of the ''Dark Void'' theme, which was, originally, an [[April Fools' Day|April fools]] joke. However, the theme was used for the prequel, ''Dark Void Zero''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Diener|first=Matt|title=Interview with Bear McCreary (April 2011)|url=http://www.squareenixmusic.com/features/interviews/bearmccreary.shtml| publisher= Squareenixmusic.com| accessdate=June 29, 2014|date=April 2011}}</ref> He composed all the songs in an eight-bit fashion by connecting the wires on an actual [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] console and cartridge to create authenticity.\n\nHe arranged James Rolfe's ''[[The Angry Video Game Nerd]]'' \"[[You're a Mean One, Mr. Grinch]]\" parody \"You're a Mean One, Mr. Nerd\" for the 2010 Christmas special, with orchestra and eight-bit audio elements.<ref>{{cite web|last=Napolitano|first=Jayson|title=Bear McCreary Vs. The Angry Video Game Nerd: A Christmas Special|url=http://www.originalsoundversion.com/bear-mccreary-vs-the-angry-video-game-nerd-a-christmas-special/|publisher=Original Sound Version|accessdate=June 29, 2014|date=December 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcCreary also performed with his orchestra band live at Sony's E3 2016 press conference throughout the show and composed the score of the new ''[[God of War (2018 video game)|God of War]]'' game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis|first=Justin|title=E3 2016: New God of War Announced|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/06/14/e3-2016-new-god-of-war-announced/| publisher= [[IGN.com]]|accessdate=June 14, 2016|date=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcCreary married singer/songwriter Raya Yarbrough in 2010. They have collaborated on the music of ''Battlestar Galactica'', \u2018\u2019Outlander\u2019\u2019, ''Defiance'', ''Da Vinci's Demons'', among other projects.<ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Getting Married!!|url=http://www.bearmccreary.com/blog/?p=1536|publisher= BearMcCreary.com| first= Bear| last= McCreary| accessdate=February 29, 2012 |date= February 24, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malibu Wedding Photographer|url=http://larryreeves.info/malibu-wedding-photographer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905044629/http://larryreeves.info/malibu-wedding-photographer/|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 5, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> Their daughter Sonatine, named after the musical term ''[[sonatina]]'', was born on June 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title= Sonatine Yarbrough McCreary|url= http://www.bearmccreary.com/blog/blog/other/sonatine-yarbrough-mccreary/ |publisher= BearMcCreary.com| first= Bear| last= McCreary| accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n==Other influences==\nMcCreary credits composers [[Jerry Goldsmith]], Elmer Bernstein, [[Danny Elfman]], [[Ennio Morricone]], [[John Williams]], [[Shirley Walker]] as being key to his growing up adoring film music. They were his heroes while he was growing up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barnett|first=Barbara|title=A Conversation with Outlander Composer Bear McCreary|url=https://www.barbarabarnett.com/2016/07/a-conversation-with-outlander-composer-bear-mccreary/|publisher=Original Sound Version|accessdate=July 29, 2016|date=July 29, 2016}}</ref> Contemporary composers including [[Hans Zimmer]] continue to inspire McCreary's growth.\n\n==Works==\n\n===Film scores===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n!Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2004\n|''[[My Baby's Daddy]]''\n|[[Cheryl Dunye]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Additional music<br>Score composed by [[Richard Gibbs]]\n|-\n|''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]''\n|[[Christopher Erskin]]\n|-\n| 2006\n|''[[Rest Stop (film)|Rest Stop]]''\n|[[John Shiban]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Wrong Turn 2: Dead End]]''\n|[[Joe Lynch (director)|Joe Lynch]]\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n|''[[Rest Stop: Don't Look Back]]''\n|Shawn Papazian\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n|''[[Step Up 3D]]''\n|[[Jon M. Chu]]\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n|''[[Chillerama]]''\n|[[Joe Lynch (director)|Joe Lynch]]\n| Segment: \"Zom-B Movie\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n|''[[Europa Report]]''\n|[[Sebasti\u00e1n Cordero]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Knights of Badassdom]]''\n|[[Joe Lynch (director)|Joe Lynch]]\n| Provided Vocals for Joe's singing voice\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n|''[[Angry Video Game Nerd: The Movie]]''\n|Kevin Finn<br>[[James Rolfe]]\n|''AVGN'' themes by Kyle Justin\n|-\n| ''[[Everly (film)|Everly]]''\n|[[Joe Lynch (director)|Joe Lynch]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2016\n|''[[The Forest (2016 film)|The Forest]]''\n|[[Jason Zada]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Boy (2016 film)|The Boy]]''\n|[[William Brent Bell]]\n|Nominated- [[World Soundtrack Awards|World Soundtrack Award for Discovery of the Year]]\n|-\n| ''[[10 Cloverfield Lane]]''\n|[[Dan Trachtenberg]]\n|Nominated- [[Hollywood Music in Media Award for Best Original Song in a Sci-Fi, Fantasy or Horror Film|HMMA Award for Best Original Song in a Sci-Fi, Fantasy or Horror Film]]<br>Nominated- [[World Soundtrack Awards|World Soundtrack 